When calling `when(spyClass.functionB(any(),any()).thenReturn(mockString)`, it will indeed go through the real method in debug mode. But the method is mocked, and your `functionA` gets the `mockString`. It does work. I don&#39;t really understand why seing that you can go into debug mode into it is a problem.

To answer the question, using `mock` won&#39;t go through the method: 

    Class mockClass = mock(Class.class);

	when(mockClass.functionB(any(),any())).thenReturn(mockString);
	when(mockClass.functionA(arguments)).thenCallRealMethod();

	mockClass.functionA(arguments);

**BUT** : this is a really bad test, you should never need to do that (spy or mock). If you test a class, then you test all of it. 
**If you need to mock a method to test another one, one of them probably belongs to another class.**

Or in the situation when the tested class for eg. ClassA has a methodA() which calls inside methodB() and you are not interested at all of what happens inside methodB() then you could simply use an spy on the object representing the current class under test then set the custom behaviour of the methodB() using for eg. **Mockito.doNothing().when()** + **@Spy**.

    
    @InjectMocks
    @Spy
    private ClassA testObj;
    
    @BeforeEach
    public void setUp() {
    
    	super.setUp();
    	
    // the actual call of the methodB() will be totally ignored
    	doNothing().when(testObj).methodB(input);
    }
    
    @Test
    public void methodTest() {}

